    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents of a genetic component often cite twin and adoption studies, aiming to separate heritability from environmental influence. These researchers frequently use heritability estimates from behavioral genetics to suggest that a significant portion of variance in cognitive traits is genetically influenced. They also point to genetic markers and studies of cognitive function in twin pairs residing in different environments as supporting evidence for genetic underpinnings. However, this body of work is highly controversial and faces substantial criticism regarding interpretation and confounding variables.",
      "source": "target",
