      "content": "The controversial literature often interprets group differences in IQ scores as fixed traits, claiming statistical hierarchies exist between different racial groups. These arguments frequently rely on aggregating IQ data from large-scale studies and generalizing them to define group-level differences. They conclude that observed mean score differences reflect underlying, biologically-determined aptitudes between populations. It is crucial to note that these conclusions are heavily contested by the broader scientific community due to methodological limitations in these comparative studies.",
